    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.43-44_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial"> Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">43</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    Columbia University
                        <lb/>
                    in the City of New York
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">DEPARTMENT OF ANTHROPOLOGY</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 11, 1932</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr Nei<del/><add>h</add>ardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It was a pleasure to have your letter and I regret greatly that I have been so slow in acknowledging its arrival. I am trying to put all my notes into shape before starting west on another field trip, and time out for pleasant things doesn't come much into my schedule these days.</p>
                
                <p>I should be very proud to have a copy of your <hi rend="caps">SONG OF THE INDIAN WARS</hi>. If you <del/><add>will</add> autograph it and send it to me at your convenience, I assure you it will always be a prized possession.</p>
                
                <p>You may be certain that I am not only happy, but passionately eager, to say everything I can in favor of your <hi rend="caps">BLACK ELK SPEAKS</hi> to everyone I talk with who is of the sort to really take in its significance. I have already done so in many an instance, calling attention<del>,</del>(to it)of the Folklore professor here, for one.</p>
                
                <p>Please forgive my tardiness in replying to your gracious letter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Ella Deloria</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>I have several speaking engagements next fall and shall mention the book as well-worth reading by any who sincerely want to try <hi rend="caps">UNDERSTANDING</hi> the Indian's life-philosophy.</p>
                </postscript>
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.43-44_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">44</fw>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S</hi></opener> <p>It may perhaps interest you to know that I had an opportunity of recommending it as collateral reading for the Episcopal Woman's Auxillary of the New York Diocese because the two subjects for their Mission study are China, and the North American Indian.</p>
                </postscript>
                
                <note type="recipient">Ella Deloria Sioux Indian, Prof. Anthropology at Columbia, etc. See other letter on "Black Elk"</note>
                
            </div1>
